President Joe Biden has announced his intent to nominate several individuals for key leadership positions in his administration. 

Cara L. Abercrombie is nominated for Assistant Secretary of Defense for Acquisition. She currently serves as Deputy Assistant to the President and Coordinator for Defense Policy and Arms Control at the National Security Council. Abercrombie has extensive experience in defense, having held various positions in the Office of the Secretary of Defense since 2003. She is also a recipient of the Presidential Rank Award of Distinguished Executive.

Tobin John Bradley is nominated for Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to the Republic of Guatemala. He is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and currently serves as Deputy Assistant Secretary of State in the Bureau of International Narcotics and Law Enforcement Affairs. Bradley has held positions in Mexico, at the National Security Council, and at U.S. embassies in London, Amman, and Iraq.

Jeffery Martin Baran is nominated for Commissioner on the Nuclear Regulatory Commission. He is currently a member of the commission and has been since October 2014. Prior to that, Baran served as Staff Director for Energy and Environment for the U.S. House of Representatives Committee on Energy and Commerce.

Betty Y. Jang is nominated for Trustee of the Harry S. Truman Scholarship Foundation. She has served on the foundation's Board of Trustees since February 2022. Jang has over 25 years of legal, compliance, and leadership experience, having worked as a general counsel, practiced law, and taught as an adjunct professor. She is also involved in various bar associations and scholarship programs.

These nominations highlight President Biden's choices for key positions in defense, diplomacy, nuclear regulation, and scholarship.